Once you accept that viral structures this large could exist (and obviously it would require a method of replication even stranger than Pandoravirus), then they certainly could evolve mimicry in order to get hosts to consume them without needing any intelligence. Pandoravirus itself mimics bacteria in order to get the host protozoan to engulf it. Human action has caused significant biomimetic adaptations in the evolution of other organisms, for example the shells of Heikeopsis japonica. The accelerated pace of evolution here is anomalous, but the end result itself isn't, and doesn't require an intelligent designer.





